  "prompt": "Is it true that diet soda kills brain cells because they use so many chemicals to make it \"diet\"?",
  "response": "There is no strong scientific evidence to support the claim that diet soda kills brain cells. Diet sodas often contain artificial sweeteners, such as aspartame, that have been rigorously tested for safety. While some studies have suggested potential adverse effects of artificial sweeteners, most regulatory agencies, including the U.S. Food and Drug Administration (FDA), the European Food Safety Authority (EFSA), and others, have deemed them safe for consumption within established daily intake limits.\n\nConcerns about artificial sweeteners often stem from isolated studies or anecdotal reports, but comprehensive reviews and large-scale studies have not conclusively demonstrated that these sweeteners cause significant harm to brain cells or overall neurological health when consumed in moderation.\n\nHowever, it is crucial to maintain a balanced diet and be mindful of overall consumption of processed foods and drinks, including diet sodas. If you have specific health concerns or conditions, it's always best to consult with a healthcare professional.",
